man: habitational name from Linne (Lower Saxony), or North German topographic name equivalent to   Linde   1 ‘lime tree’.","Swedish (<b>Linné</b>): topographic or ornamental name derived from <i>lind</i> ‘linden tree, lime tree’, a cognate of 1 above. The original humanistic form of the surname, <b>Linnæus</b>, is still found in Sweden.","History: The most famous bearer of the Swedish surname <i>Linné</i> was botanist Carl von Linné (1707–78), born <i>Linnæus</i>. The surname <i>Linnæus</i> was adopted by Carl's father Nils Ingemarsson after a giant linden tree that grew on his homestead."],"variants":[{"name":"Linde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Gunner, Lars.  German Kurt, Dieter, Erna, Fritz, Hasso, Markus, Otto, Ralf.","German, Dutch, and Scandinavian: topographic name for someone who lived by a conspicuous lime tree, Middle High German, Dutch <i>linde</i>, Scandinavian <i>lind</i>. There are several places, especially in northern Germany, named with this word, and the name may be a habitational name from any of these. The word was also used in a number of Old High German women's personal names, with the meaning ‘shield’ or ‘spear’ (these being made from the hard wood of the lime); it is possible that the surname in some cases is from a short form of one of these. As a Swedish name it is often ornamental rather than topographic. Compare   Lindy  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German <i>Linde</i> ‘lime tree’ (see 1 above)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mahaut de Ligne was born about 1210, in Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium, her father, Fastre De Ligne, was 32 and her mother, Brigitte van Gavre, was 20. She had at least 1 daughter with Jacques I de Thiant, Seigneur de Werchin et Longueville. She died in 1274, at the age of 65."},"et":{"about 1210–1274":"umbes 1210–1274","1210–1274":"1210–1274","1203–1264":"1203–1264","1235–1284":"1235–1284","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1246"